  <div class="page">
    <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/en/">Home</a> › <a href="/en/">Family Law</a> › Divorce Litigation</div>
    <h1>Divorce Litigation</h1>
    <p class="lead">Litigation is strategy, not aggression. An experienced litigator knows when to push, when to negotiate, and when to ask the court to intervene — always keeping your actual interests first.</p>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>WHAT IS DIVORCE LITIGATION?</h2>
      <p>Divorce litigation is the process of resolving marriage breakdown and related issues — property, children, support — through the Ontario Family Court system. Litigation does not mean fighting to the end. A skilled lawyer uses the court process as leverage to achieve the best possible outcome, whether that is a negotiated settlement or a court order.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>WHAT WE HANDLE</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Contested and uncontested divorce at the Ontario Superior Court of Justice</li>
        <li>Financial disclosure motions</li>
        <li>Equalization of Net Family Property</li>
        <li>Matrimonial home — forced sale orders</li>
        <li>High-conflict litigation strategy</li>
        <li>Costs awards and enforcement</li>
        <li>Cross-border divorce involving China</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>VERIFIED CASE — Yang v. Li, 2024 ONSC 4801</h2>
      <p>Represented the respondent against eight simultaneous claims including a CBV business valuation dispute. All claims defeated at motion. Significant costs awarded for opposing counsel's lack of candour. Appeal unanimously dismissed by three Divisional Court judges.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does divorce litigation take in Ontario?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">A simple uncontested divorce can be finalized in 4–6 months. Contested litigation typically takes 1–3 years depending on complexity, disclosure issues, and court scheduling. An experienced litigator can often resolve cases faster through strategic motions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between a motion and a trial?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">A motion is a court hearing on a specific issue — financial disclosure, interim support, or possession of the matrimonial home. A trial is the final determination of all outstanding issues. Many cases settle after motions without ever reaching trial.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do I have to go to court?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Not necessarily. Many cases settle through negotiation or mediation. However, having an experienced litigator on your side strengthens your position at every stage — including the negotiating table.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card cta">
